The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Metro | Short film fest back in town
                                                                                                                         3                                                                                      Short film fest back in town
                          A still from Betty B and   the The rsquo;s of Germany                    
	The Kalpanirjhar International Short Fiction Film Festival will begin at Max Mueller Bhavan on November 1 and continue till November 5.         
	Organised by the Kalpanirjhar Foundation and Goethe-Institut/Max Mueller Bhavan and with Patton as co-sponsor, the eighth edition of the film fest brings to Calcutta a clutch of international and national shorts, many of them award-winning entries at film competitions.         
	The festival will be inaugurated on Monday at 6pm by Paul Holmes, a lecturer in direction at Screen Academy Scotland, and open with Party (Tulum) from Croatia, followed by shorts from Germany, the UK and India.         
	Day II will see Crossing Boundaries  an international selection of films from Belarus to Poland to Israel.         
	Other than entries from film/media schools like Screen Academy Scotland, FTII, Pune, Whistling Woods International, Mumbai and various German institutes, the festival will see 20 animation films from the National Institute of Design, Ahmedabad.         
	Another highlight is five films on Basque, Spain.         
	This year, 21 entries will vie for the Patton Award for the Best Indian Short Fiction Film of the Year, which was bagged last year by FTII entry Gaarud (The Spell).         
	As part of the festival, Holmes will conduct a script-writing workshop, supported by British Council Calcutta, between 2-4 November.                                                                                                                                                          
